WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.001 --> 00:00:05.280
My background is that I have served in military intelligence for most of my career.

00:00:05.280 --> 00:00:09.840
I am an officer and an intelligence colonel who retired last fall.

00:00:09.840 --> 00:00:13.840
I started here in January at the University as a teacher. I teach intelligence. 

00:00:13.840 --> 00:00:21.520
As I have spent most of my career in intelligence, Russia and the Soviet Union have always been my point of interest. 

00:00:21.520 --> 00:00:27.720
In 1986, as a young lieutenant, I was sent to what was then Leningrad to study the Russian language.

00:00:27.720 --> 00:00:31.600
Even then I started to wonder why the Russians were doing things differently than we do? (in the western world)

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:33.760
Why do they see the world differently than we see it?

00:00:33.782 --> 00:00:39.560
Since then, I have worked with the Russians and with the Soviets until my retirement.

00:00:39.560 --> 00:00:45.160
I’ve been to the Soviet Union and to Russia a lot during my career and been in a lot of contact with them.

00:00:45.160 --> 00:00:49.600
I’ve always wondered why they thought things differently.

00:00:49.600 --> 00:01:00.200
Then when I started writing my PhD here at the University I discovered the theory of strategic culture.

00:01:00.200 --> 00:01:07.960
That theory opened up how to rationalize and think about why Russians do things differently than we do.

00:01:07.960 --> 00:01:12.680
This strategic culture is a way (to analyze).

00:01:12.680 --> 00:01:17.840
It was created in the United States during the 1970s when the Americans lost the Vietnam War.

00:01:17.840 --> 00:01:22.040
They began to wonder how a superpower like the United States could lose to Vietnam,

00:01:22.040 --> 00:01:24.000
which Americans considered to be a very underdeveloped country.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:29.600
They realized that not everything is a plus and a minus, that is, a zero-sum game.

00:01:29.600 --> 00:01:35.360
There are other factors behind it that affect the people and how the people operate together.

00:01:35.360 --> 00:01:42.080
The Americans developed a theory of strategic culture capable of explaining about a country.

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:49.720
In this case, about Russia, how does the state leadership see a crisis?

00:01:49.720 --> 00:01:52.440
How does it see the use of force in a crisis?

00:01:52.440 --> 00:01:55.960
How does it see the role of a crisis and the use of force in foreign policy?

00:01:55.960 --> 00:01:59.840
How does it see the enemy? How does it see a threat?

00:01:59.840 --> 00:02:05.560
And then how does it envision the possible strategic options by which it might respond to a threat?

00:02:05.560 --> 00:02:08.680
This theory of strategic culture explains it.

00:02:08.680 --> 00:02:16.200
The theory of strategic culture is based on trying to outline what factors influence the decision-making of the state leadership.

00:02:16.200 --> 00:02:24.000
It then looks at how things are reflected in government decision-making and how they are reflected in practical action.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:30.600
This is a pretty good way to explain the actions of a state, in this case Russia.

00:02:30.600 --> 00:02:33.160
On why Russia has acted as it has.

00:02:33.160 --> 00:02:39.000
This will help us understand. When I say understand, I do not mean that we have to approve of what Russia is doing.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:42.640
But it helps us understand why Russia does things differently. 

00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:47.240
It may even give us the instruments to predict what may happen next.

00:02:47.240 --> 00:02:57.680
Churchill said in 1939 that "Russia is a riddle, wrapped in a mystery, inside an enigma." It is true.

00:02:57.680 --> 00:02:58.960
This is well said.

00:02:58.960 --> 00:03:04.080
Let us now set out to dispel this riddle through the theory of strategic culture.

00:03:04.080 --> 00:03:09.720
Before we start with that, we must remember that we do not have one Russia.

00:03:09.720 --> 00:03:13.920
We kind of have many layers of Russia.

00:03:13.920 --> 00:03:21.560
Different historical layers that still influence the thinking of the Russians about how the Russians work today.

00:03:21.560 --> 00:03:31.480
If we start from that very first movement, that is, Slavic Russia. Language and entity and Russianness were born there.

00:03:31.480 --> 00:03:37.480
Also the belief that all Slavic people, as it were, are one was created there.

00:03:37.480 --> 00:03:46.640
And the Russian people, the largest of the Slavic peoples, have the duty of keeping them all in check and protecting them.

00:03:46.640 --> 00:03:49.240
When we go further in history. 

00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:54.640
With the fall of Constantinople, the traditions of Eastern Rome were transferred to Moscow.

00:03:54.640 --> 00:03:58.240
Moscow uses the term third and eternal Rome for itself. 

00:03:58.240 --> 00:04:02.480
The Russians are, as it were, followers of the Eastern Roman tradition.

00:04:02.480 --> 00:04:08.280
Religion, conservatism and the relationship to authority came from there.

00:04:08.280 --> 00:04:12.960
It means that one does not challenge authority. Authority is obtained from God.

00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:18.440
He who leads us has received authority from God to lead us. He is infallible.

00:04:18.440 --> 00:04:21.480
Authority will not be challenged under any circumstances. 

00:04:21.480 --> 00:04:25.120
This idea comes from Byzantine Russia.

00:04:26.920 --> 00:04:33.640
The third era that influenced Russian thought in a great manner is Mongol Russia.

00:04:33.640 --> 00:04:37.080
In the 1240s, the Mongols conquered Russia.

00:04:37.080 --> 00:04:41.440
They held Russia for 150 years. That time was cruel.

00:04:41.440 --> 00:04:49.960
There are a lot of words in Russian, related to torture, taxation and corruption, that come from the Mongol language.

00:04:49.960 --> 00:04:54.680
Dominance under personal authority was rooted in the administrative culture from the Mongols.

00:04:54.680 --> 00:04:57.680
That is, there is only one khan that leads.

00:04:57.680 --> 00:05:01.520
It is he who leads, no one else.

00:05:01.520 --> 00:05:07.640
Others are passive followers. That one guy leads and takes responsibility and the initiative.

00:05:07.640 --> 00:05:13.480
When the belief of divine legitimacy to lead is attached to this, the leader will appear as fairly tough in their world view.

00:05:13.480 --> 00:05:16.480
The corruption and cruelty also comes from the Mongol era. 

00:05:16.480 --> 00:05:26.600
During the Mongol rule the only ways to survive were lying, corruption and violence.

00:05:26.600 --> 00:05:31.360
This still lives very deep in Russia’s strategic culture. 

00:05:31.360 --> 00:05:35.960
When Mongol rule ended, the Mongols did not just pack their bags and disappear from Russia.

00:05:35.960 --> 00:05:38.120
Instead they mixed with the locals. 

00:05:38.120 --> 00:05:41.920
So the traditions also stayed with the people. In particular, to the leading caste.

00:05:41.920 --> 00:05:48.720
The Mongols who had previously ruled the country merged into the ruling layers, which is still visible today.

00:05:48.720 --> 00:05:52.840
When looking at genetic inheritance, they are pretty dark, dark eyes for example.

00:05:52.840 --> 00:05:55.040
 There are not many blondes in Russia.

00:05:56.200 --> 00:06:01.120
Then came this era of turmoil. Although it was a a short period of time, it had a great importance to the Russians. 

00:06:01.120 --> 00:06:06.960
Because then both external and internal enemies roared.

00:06:06.960 --> 00:06:11.040
 The Poles who conquered Moscow and Russia did not have a strong leader.

00:06:11.040 --> 00:06:21.240
Romanov was then elected Tsar and the Russians realized that a strong leader was better than chaos.

00:06:21.240 --> 00:06:28.440
In addition to all this when the authority comes from God and the autocrat is indeed a leader.

00:06:28.440 --> 00:06:34.000
It was stated there that only sovereignty will save Russia.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:41.040
It has been several hundred years in their genetic inheritance that autocracy is the only right solution.

00:06:41.040 --> 00:06:43.600
 That is, autocracy is better than chaos and mayhem.

00:06:44.680 --> 00:06:46.960
Then we came to European Russia.

00:06:46.960 --> 00:06:53.960
Peter the Great founded the city of St. Petersburg in the early 18th century on that Finnish swamp to the Neva estuary.

00:06:55.040 --> 00:07:00.480
After that, the Russians began to clash whether they were in the West or in the East.

00:07:00.480 --> 00:07:05.400
The Westernizers (Západniki) favored the West and the Slavophiles favored the East.

00:07:05.400 --> 00:07:07.960
This struggle is still going on.

00:07:07.960 --> 00:07:16.480
Russia began to rise into a great power. As Russia modernized, they also started to mystify themselves.

00:07:16.480 --> 00:07:19.560
That is, Russia itself began to mystify itself through authors for example.

00:07:19.560 --> 00:07:25.480
They kind of built a smokescreen between us and them, consciously mystifying Russia.

00:07:27.640 --> 00:07:30.760
Then came the great power of the Soviet Union and the Cold War.

00:07:30.760 --> 00:07:37.400
The power politics and the sphere of influence of Russia come from the Cold War era.

00:07:37.400 --> 00:07:42.240
World War II taught them that it is better to fight not in their own territory but on the territories of others.

00:07:42.240 --> 00:07:45.400
The Soviet Union lost more than 20 million people during World War II.

00:07:45.400 --> 00:07:52.480
Authoritarian rule has followed Russian rule since Mongol era. It hasn't changed since then.

00:07:52.480 --> 00:07:57.280
The name of the leader has changed but authoritarian rule itself has always remained the same.

00:07:57.280 --> 00:08:01.560
Russia sees itself as the heir to the Soviet Union, as it is in some respects.

00:08:01.560 --> 00:08:04.720
So these are the six layers of Russia.

00:08:04.720 --> 00:08:09.960
When we think of Russia, we always have to take into consideration that there is Mongol rule, how it affects and so on.

00:08:09.960 --> 00:08:14.720
There is not one Russia that was born in the 1990s.

00:08:14.720 --> 00:08:18.800
Instead Russia has a long tradition that goes back to the 13th century and earlier.

00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:24.720
Eleven time zones in Russia. These huge distances also affect Russia. 

00:08:24.720 --> 00:08:27.240
One interesting thing, this area.

00:08:27.240 --> 00:08:35.920
From the Polish border to Moscow, through to Urals, is a plateau that is easy to attack with both horses and tanks.

00:08:35.920 --> 00:08:40.400
That is what has been done. Napoleon attacked, the Germans attacked and so on.

00:08:40.400 --> 00:08:43.360
That idea is also in the genetic inheritance of the Russians

00:08:43.360 --> 00:08:46.600
That someone is always attacking. "We will be conquered".

00:08:46.600 --> 00:08:56.480
They have no shelter, no mountains, no rivers. There are no lakes between the east and the capital. 

00:08:56.480 --> 00:09:03.560
Geographically, Russia has always been easy to conquer, which also influences their thinking.

00:09:04.640 --> 00:09:14.080
Belief in Russianness. Russianness consists of three things. It is orthodoxy, autocracy, and narodnost.

00:09:14.080 --> 00:09:19.440
There is no Finnish translation for Narodnost, but it means the people or things related to the ordinary people.

00:09:19.440 --> 00:09:23.080
We do not have such a word in Finnish. Let's open that point more.

00:09:23.080 --> 00:09:25.960
But first the autocracy.

00:09:25.960 --> 00:09:31.400
They have always been an autocracy since Mongolian times. 

00:09:31.400 --> 00:09:35.160
Either it has been a Khan, or it has been a Tsar.

00:09:35.160 --> 00:09:40.160
Or it has been a communist party usually personified by Stalin or Khrushchev or anyone.

00:09:40.160 --> 00:09:45.360
Or now for the president. 

00:09:45.360 --> 00:09:49.960
Russia has strong autocracy. They also want autocracy because they are used to it.

00:09:49.960 --> 00:09:56.160
A good leader keeps confusion away. They think this way and are used to it.

00:09:57.640 --> 00:10:02.480
Conservatives have held power in Russia for 200-300 years. 

00:10:02.480 --> 00:10:09.800
There were a few radical reformers: Peter the Great, his reforms were mostly successful. 

00:10:09.800 --> 00:10:13.960
The reforms of these other gentlemen were mostly not successful.

00:10:13.960 --> 00:10:18.800
Someone can, of course, consider Lenin's accomplishments as a success or Gorbachevs.

00:10:18.800 --> 00:10:21.600
But the Russians themselves see for example that Gorbachev disintegrated the Soviet Union.

00:10:21.600 --> 00:10:29.440
Nor was Yeltsin a super reformer. In other words, the Conservatives have always held power.

00:10:31.960 --> 00:10:34.480
The Russians believe in a just Tsar.

00:10:34.480 --> 00:10:40.920
Once the Tsar has taken authority from God, he cannot make mistakes.

00:10:40.920 --> 00:10:45.360
The Tsar is infallible.

00:10:45.360 --> 00:10:55.320
He has princes who gradually become infallible near the Tsar.

00:10:56.480 --> 00:11:03.080
Some prince becomes a Tsar in due course. The infallible Tsar who is always right.

00:11:03.080 --> 00:11:06.440
The mistakes are happening here within the boyars.

00:11:06.440 --> 00:11:13.520
Between the people and the infallible Tsar, there is a boyars. 

00:11:13.520 --> 00:11:18.800
Boyars, which at different times are from a slightly different social class.

00:11:18.800 --> 00:11:23.720
Boyars as an institution were born as early as the 9th century. 

00:11:23.720 --> 00:11:26.600
Their position in the hierarchy came after the princes.

00:11:26.600 --> 00:11:33.720
We have a Tsar who is infallible, princes who grow into a tsar some of whom become infallible when they become Tsars. 

00:11:33.720 --> 00:11:36.720
Then there are the people. In between the prince and the people are the boyars,

00:11:36.720 --> 00:11:41.040
who make the right decisions of a wise Tsar, sometimes wrong.

00:11:42.360 --> 00:11:46.160
If an error occurs somewhere, it is the boyars who have made that error.

00:11:46.160 --> 00:11:51.960
The Tsar, the President or the Secretary-General of the Central Committee is always infallible.

00:11:51.960 --> 00:11:54.240
The fault is found in the boyars.

00:11:55.160 --> 00:12:02.800
After a period of turmoil, the boyars completely lost their power over the Tsar and their property as well.

00:12:02.800 --> 00:12:07.040
That was during the turmoil era, ownership changed.

00:12:07.040 --> 00:12:10.400
Previously, they had ownership, but it became tenure.

00:12:10.400 --> 00:12:14.520
That is, the Tsar took everything away and gave tenure to boyars.

00:12:14.520 --> 00:12:19.240
"You get to control this state or you get to control these slaves. You get to control this merchant ship." and so on.

00:12:19.240 --> 00:12:22.200
But tenure can be taken away if you misbehave.

00:12:22.200 --> 00:12:24.680
If the Tsar is not satisfied, the possession will be taken away from you.

00:12:24.680 --> 00:12:27.600
That is, ownership became tenure.

00:12:27.600 --> 00:12:34.040
During the Soviet era, tenure continued instead of ownership.

00:12:34.040 --> 00:12:38.680
That is, in the Soviet Union when you reached a certain position of power you had tenure.

00:12:38.680 --> 00:12:42.960
You got to visit a dacha and the Yalta and you had a servant who was looking out for you. 

00:12:42.960 --> 00:12:46.320
However, you did not own these, but you had possession, a tenure of these.

00:12:46.320 --> 00:12:51.640
Another point is that when you reach a certain position, you are entitled to a certain amount of corruption.

00:12:51.640 --> 00:12:57.480
That is, a certain degree of power gives you the right to a certain degree of corruption, too.

00:12:57.480 --> 00:13:03.720
At a lower rank, you didn’t get to steal that much. The higher you get, the more you get to steal. It had rules.

00:13:03.720 --> 00:13:08.240
Those rules had to be followed, they weren’t written rules, of course, but everyone knew these rules of the game.

00:13:08.240 --> 00:13:14.200
This same system is currently in Russia.

00:13:14.200 --> 00:13:23.800
The nomenclature tells who is on what scale compared to everyone else and how much corruption he is allowed to take.

00:13:23.800 --> 00:13:28.720
These business oligarchs also belong to this group.

00:13:28.720 --> 00:13:35.400
The rules are as follows: You must not steal from the wrong guy or you're not allowed to steal more than your position allows you to.

00:13:35.400 --> 00:13:37.800
You only steal the amount of your position in the hierarchy.

00:13:37.800 --> 00:13:48.800
Here are some of these boyars. There was a live broadcast last summer. Putin was on television and took the boyars with him.

00:13:48.800 --> 00:13:53.680
Here are the governors of different regions in Russia.

00:13:53.680 --> 00:13:58.720
A man called Putin on television and said, for example "In our area this road network is in poor condition?" 

00:13:58.720 --> 00:14:03.920
Putin asked the governor of the area "Why the roads are in poor condition, fix them".

00:14:03.920 --> 00:14:09.760
The governor replies, "Yes, Mr. President." The caller says "Thank you Mr. President, that you took care of this too."

00:14:09.760 --> 00:14:15.320
That is, the boyar procedure still works. It was even done publicly on television.

00:14:15.320 --> 00:14:20.000
If you reach a certain position then you will get a certain share of corruption.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:22.040
Neither too much nor from the wrong guy.

00:14:22.040 --> 00:14:26.120
Here's a person who stole too much.

00:14:26.120 --> 00:14:32.760
Khodorkovsky, stole too much, 10 years in prison. Currently living in Switzerland.

00:14:32.760 --> 00:14:40.200
Ulyukayev stole from the wrong person, Sechin, who is close to Putin and probably the second most influential person in Russia.

00:14:40.200 --> 00:14:45.360
Ulyukayev went to steal from Sechin, 10 years in prison.

00:14:45.360 --> 00:14:51.160
That is, if you follow the rules, everything will go well, if you don’t follow the rules, you suffer.

00:14:51.160 --> 00:14:53.240
This is how it works.

00:14:53.240 --> 00:14:55.480
Then there is the religion.

00:14:55.480 --> 00:15:00.680
Religion is important because it unites people together. This is Putin's inauguration.

00:15:00.680 --> 00:15:04.600
Here is Patriarch Kirill of Moscow and All Russia.

00:15:04.600 --> 00:15:07.760
Look where they stand.

00:15:07.760 --> 00:15:13.360
First Schröder, the Prime Minister is behind him.

00:15:13.360 --> 00:15:20.360
Minister of Defense at the rear. It is no coincidence that the patriarch stands first.

00:15:20.360 --> 00:15:25.200
That is, Kirill belongs to the boyars as well and his job is to swear faith in people. 

00:15:25.200 --> 00:15:29.720
"Even though it goes a little bad now, when we get to heaven, it will go really well there."

00:15:29.720 --> 00:15:32.560
That is his job in the system.

00:15:32.560 --> 00:15:38.800
Of course Putin. The story goes that he has even been baptized secretly. Believes who believes.

00:15:38.800 --> 00:15:46.080
In any case, he was a member of the Communist Party and an officer of the KGB. He is the number one believer.

00:15:46.080 --> 00:15:48.080
This is how situations change.

00:15:48.080 --> 00:15:59.080
This is Kirill. As an example the Russians found a picture where Mr. Kirill is holding a $ 30,000 watch on his wrist.

00:15:59.080 --> 00:16:04.120
I don't know what kind of salaries the priests have in Russia but my wife is a priest and she does not have such a watch. 

00:16:04.120 --> 00:16:09.480
When this became public, the Russians tried to cover it up by editing the image

00:16:09.480 --> 00:16:14.520
But forgot to edit the clock reflection off the table surface.

00:16:14.520 --> 00:16:19.680
In this way, the boyars are sometimes caught.

00:16:19.680 --> 00:16:25.760
Then the third component, namely the people, narodnost.

00:16:26.680 --> 00:16:35.720
In the 19th century, after the French Revolution, there was a lot of talk about the people and what kind of role people in the community have and so on.

00:16:35.720 --> 00:16:42.360
In Russia, it was also considered, from the leaders perspective and was determined what narodnost is.

00:16:42.360 --> 00:16:45.200
It is Russia's own version of the people.

00:16:45.200 --> 00:16:52.680
The Tsar knew better than the people themselves what was good for the people. The Tsar is infallible.

00:16:52.680 --> 00:16:59.800
When a leader has received power from God, he knows better what is good for the people.

00:16:59.800 --> 00:17:08.680
During the Soviet era, this continued in the same way under communism.

00:17:08.680 --> 00:17:14.360
During the Soviet era, on the roofs of the houses read "the party and the people are one," although they were certainly not the same, but the roofs of the houses read so.

00:17:14.360 --> 00:17:22.320
Narod and narodnost was a big deal. This is still evident in Russia.

00:17:22.320 --> 00:17:24.960
The Russians have the ability to expect and endure a tremendous amount of suffering.

00:17:24.960 --> 00:17:31.120
This is an amazing trait for them. They are able to anticipate and endure suffering.

00:17:31.120 --> 00:17:33.920
They have made suffering as if it was a virtue.

00:17:34.880 --> 00:17:42.400
When you suffer on behalf of the Soviet Union or Russia, things turn out really nice when all that is over.

00:17:42.400 --> 00:17:48.680
For example, when you die or when you reach communism. 

00:17:48.680 --> 00:17:54.760
"There are no refrigerators and no real food, but when we get to communism then there will be everything."

00:17:54.760 --> 00:17:58.400
 The Russians have a miraculous ability to endure suffering.

00:17:58.400 --> 00:18:01.600
On the other hand, they also have a wonderful way of forming two realities.

00:18:01.600 --> 00:18:06.520
They formed a Soviet public reality and a kitchen table reality.

00:18:06.520 --> 00:18:08.000
Around the kitchen table things were really being discussed.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:11.040
I had a chat at the kitchen table in 1986, extremely interesting.

00:18:11.040 --> 00:18:13.120
Perestroika was about to start just then.

00:18:13.120 --> 00:18:19.080
It was interesting because they are like two different people when they go outside compared to how they're around the kitchen table.

00:18:19.080 --> 00:18:25.520
There are two different realities that are still operating in Russia.

00:18:25.520 --> 00:18:36.360
Here is Mikhail Glinka, who in the 19th century composed the opera "A Life for the Tsar"

00:18:36.360 --> 00:18:42.600
in which a peasant sacrifices himself for the Tsar in order for the Tsar to be saved from the gut and against the Poles when Russia went to war.

00:18:42.600 --> 00:18:49.400
The sacrificer, a peasant, is a person belonging to the narodnost. He sacrificed himself so that the Tsar would be saved.

00:18:49.400 --> 00:18:56.000
It's no coincidence that in 2004 Russia issued a stamp from this same opera.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:02.520
That is, people are still told that it is the their job to sacrifice themselves for the Tsar.

00:19:02.520 --> 00:19:05.760
"Do not forget the role of you as a people."

00:19:07.040 --> 00:19:11.640
During the Soviet era, the Homo Sovieticus was created.

00:19:11.640 --> 00:19:18.960
They initially believed that the Soviet system could create a better person, who would be called the Homo Sovieticus.

00:19:18.960 --> 00:19:31.600
In fact, some others then quickly changed it to have an another meaning, how it really was seen:

00:19:31.600 --> 00:19:36.960
Careless, does not care about common property,

00:19:38.400 --> 00:19:44.160
passively accepts everything given by the director, avoids individual responsibility and so on.

00:19:44.160 --> 00:19:48.960
Whoever has been in Russia and in the Soviet Union could wonder for themselves whether these traits resemble reality or not.

00:19:48.960 --> 00:19:55.480
Then, in 1987, when the Soviet Union began to collapse,

00:19:55.480 --> 00:20:05.080
Yuri Levada, who later founded the Levada Research Center, estimated that Homo Sovieticus was on the brink of extinction.

00:20:05.080 --> 00:20:12.880
In 1994, 75% of Russian respondents said that the break-up of the Soviet Union was more bad than good.

00:20:12.880 --> 00:20:25.040
In 1998, the word democracy began in Russian minds to resemble the same as chaos.

00:20:25.040 --> 00:20:30.480
That is, only a strong leader will save us from chaos. 

00:20:30.480 --> 00:20:36.760
Then, in the late 1990s, Homo Sovieticus was, after all, alive and waiting for a strong leader.

00:20:42.240 --> 00:20:50.360
Here are the sayings of Nikolai the First, this could be Vladimir the First, who is currently in power.

00:20:50.360 --> 00:20:57.080
 "Autocracy, orthodoxy and 'Russkiy mir' - or the Russian world - must be assembled under the protection of the wings of the Russian double eagle"

00:20:57.080 --> 00:21:01.240
And that "Russia's sacred mission is to act as a messenger of a higher civilization." 

00:21:01.240 --> 00:21:07.880
And: "A little warfare in the border areas is needed to maintain a patriotic spirit."

00:21:07.880 --> 00:21:15.440
This was said in the 1800s century but this could have been said in the 2010s or in 2018.

00:21:15.440 --> 00:21:18.160
Nothing has changed.

00:21:19.280 --> 00:21:29.840
Here is Jurgen Habermas’s communicative theory, the social system, which explains how people usually think.

00:21:29.840 --> 00:21:32.680
Here it can be an individual or it could be a larger community. 

00:21:32.680 --> 00:21:38.200
It has the values ​​and norms which we are talking about today, the values and norms ​​of the strategic culture.

00:21:38.200 --> 00:21:40.960
Here at the bottom right are the facts.

00:21:40.960 --> 00:21:45.680
Facts come into our and the community's consciousness, followed by our thoughts reflecting the received facts through our values ​​and norms.

00:21:45.680 --> 00:21:53.880
Then decisions are made, specific objectives are pursued and finally we act accordingly.

00:21:53.880 --> 00:21:58.520
Strategic culture can be found here in terms of values ​​and norms.

00:21:58.520 --> 00:22:02.480
So how does this work in Russia? A little differently...

00:22:02.480 --> 00:22:07.800
80% of Russians get all their information from television.

00:22:07.800 --> 00:22:14.200
These television channels are under the control of Putin and his close associates. 

00:22:14.200 --> 00:22:19.560
That is, 80% of Russians receive filtered information.

00:22:19.560 --> 00:22:22.240
They do not get the facts from the media.

00:22:22.240 --> 00:22:33.360
In Russia the values ​​and norms are already strong and the information that is constantly being fed is different from our western point of view

00:22:33.360 --> 00:22:41.280
Therefore, it is quite certain that the goals and actions of Russians will not be the same as how we would perform in the same situations. 

00:22:41.280 --> 00:22:43.080
This difference must be remembered.

00:22:43.080 --> 00:22:50.800
More and more young people receive information from the internet because they know other languages ​​and follow information from the web. 

00:22:50.800 --> 00:22:57.840
80% of the older population still receives information through television.

00:22:57.840 --> 00:23:04.640
This is the narrative that is told on television in Russia. It is said there that Russia is a besieged fort.

00:23:04.640 --> 00:23:07.680
"NATO is besieging Russia."

00:23:07.680 --> 00:23:14.720
"Russia is at constant war with NATO. The enemy is at the gates."

00:23:14.720 --> 00:23:18.480
Here's how they see NATO's siege. 

00:23:18.480 --> 00:23:20.840
In fact, there are a few kilometers with NATO. (between Norway and Russia)

00:23:20.840 --> 00:23:24.720
Then there is the border with the Baltic states, which is really the NATO and Russian border.

00:23:24.720 --> 00:23:30.440
But this picture is being shown to them, the Russians. America also surrounds Russians both from air and from space.

00:23:32.480 --> 00:23:37.880
The only task for and within the state leadership is to stay in power.

00:23:37.880 --> 00:23:42.480
They are not much interested in the life of an ordinary Russian. Their only task is to stay in power.

00:23:42.480 --> 00:23:47.080
With this in mind, they stay in power by telling how the "enemy is at the gates, we are at war."

00:23:47.080 --> 00:23:52.600
"Only an autocrat like me can keep this country safe."

00:23:54.120 --> 00:23:56.600
"A weak leader means chaos."

00:23:56.600 --> 00:23:59.360
The enemy is at the gates and inside.

00:23:59.360 --> 00:24:07.880
According to the narrative, the West is feeding the opposition. 

00:24:07.880 --> 00:24:13.360
When the opposition raises its head, it is said to be in a conspiracy with the West against Russia and must be responded to accordingly.

00:24:13.360 --> 00:24:19.560
 80% of Russians receive this information, that Nemtsov and Navalny were western agents. 

00:24:19.560 --> 00:24:24.800
The Russians believe this story quite a lot, at least they pretend to.

00:24:24.800 --> 00:24:28.560
I don’t know how they’re talking about it at the kitchen table. 

00:24:28.560 --> 00:24:29.880
This is the story told by the Russian media under their leaders.

00:24:29.880 --> 00:24:34.760
"Russia is a besieged fort that is at constant war with the West and the enemy is inside."

00:24:35.960 --> 00:24:41.120
Putin said "Russia never lost the Cold War because it never ended." 

00:24:41.920 --> 00:24:43.960
That's how they talk there. 

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:51.920
He also said how “The Collapse of the USSR was the geopolitical tragedy of the century.” 

00:24:51.920 --> 00:24:56.800
When he says so, he also really thinks and means it himself.

00:24:56.800 --> 00:25:04.600
When Kennan was the U.S. ambassador to Moscow after World War II.

00:25:04.600 --> 00:25:10.840
He began to see how the Soviet Union would not necessarily be an ally for the United States now that Nazi Germany had been defeated.

00:25:10.840 --> 00:25:20.400
He wrote a long description of how Soviet policy was changing.

00:25:20.400 --> 00:25:28.440
He wrote "The Kremlin's neurotic view of world affairs is based on their traditional and instinctive insecurity"

00:25:28.440 --> 00:25:32.920
So the Russians have a feeling of insecurity about "someone always attacking us." 

00:25:34.560 --> 00:25:40.680
You remember the steppes up to the Urals, easy to attack with horses or with tanks or whatever. 

00:25:40.680 --> 00:25:44.880
That's how they were attacked. Napoleon attacked.

00:25:44.880 --> 00:25:48.080
The Mongols conquered most of present-day Russia.

00:25:48.080 --> 00:25:51.720
Hitler attacked and got really far into the Soviet Union. 

00:25:51.720 --> 00:25:58.680
Finns and Swedes have also been to Russia. Jacob De la Gardie was in Moscow for one winter before leaving.

00:25:58.680 --> 00:26:04.960
Then why did we have a winter war in 1939? We had a winter war because the Russians did not think we could defend our own territory.

00:26:04.960 --> 00:26:09.640
The Russians imagined the bustle coming in the direction of St. Petersburg/Leningrad.  

00:26:09.640 --> 00:26:15.080
Now evil NATO is going to attack Russia. This is the story. 

00:26:15.840 --> 00:26:21.600
"Evil NATO is now in Ukraine and attacking rebel areas." 

00:26:21.600 --> 00:26:27.360
The story is based on a neurotic sense of insecurity.

00:26:27.360 --> 00:26:32.680
This is also what Kennan wrote: "Russia is deaf to the logic of reason but very sensitive to the logic of power." 

00:26:32.680 --> 00:26:41.040
Lenin once said: "Try it with a bayonet, if it's soft, push. If it's hard, leave."

00:26:41.920 --> 00:26:50.120
In other words, if we treat Russia in the Sea of ​​Azov and in Crimea and in eastern Ukraine as before

00:26:50.120 --> 00:26:54.800
By only resenting without doing anything else, there will always be more stitches coming from Russia.

00:26:55.720 --> 00:27:00.000
But they are sensitive to the logic of power. 

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:05.760
Meaning that if there is a tough opponent against them, they leave. Kennan said it back in 1946.

00:27:05.760 --> 00:27:11.880
When a bear looks into the pond, it sees itself. Power is what works with Russia.

00:27:13.480 --> 00:27:17.560
The Russians are imperialists as are the Americans.

00:27:17.560 --> 00:27:22.320
But American imperialism is based on the fact that they want to have resources, oil, or whatever.

00:27:22.320 --> 00:27:25.360
On the other hand, Russian imperialism is based on fear.

00:27:25.360 --> 00:27:32.960
To compare, the cause and starting point of Russian imperialism is quite different. Russian imperialism is based on someone potentially attacking them again.

00:27:32.960 --> 00:27:41.280
They sought to solve this problem in the 1950s by forming the Warsaw Pact, from which they got a buffer between the enemy and themselves.

00:27:41.280 --> 00:27:46.600
Now that the Warsaw Pact has been dissolved the Russians are building the buffer a little differently now.

00:27:46.600 --> 00:27:52.880
Here is a picture in the upper right corner, the Russian S-400 air defense systems. 

00:27:52.880 --> 00:27:55.200
They are building a buffer zone in the air now.

00:27:55.200 --> 00:28:01.640
From the Kola Peninsula, the Karelian Isthmus, Kaliningrad, Crimea to Syria.

00:28:01.640 --> 00:28:07.640
They are now building the buffer zone differently. Because they can’t get land, they take air.

00:28:07.640 --> 00:28:11.600
They are taking not only air but also information.

00:28:11.600 --> 00:28:18.760
The Russians do it by pushing their own influence to the information environment. The Russians use terms like information geopolitics.

00:28:18.760 --> 00:28:26.680
Information geopolitics means that when we cannot move on land, we are advancing in the air with anti-aircraft systems and also in the information space.

00:28:26.680 --> 00:28:33.400
Russians are also seeking more protection from the information space between them and the enemy.

00:28:33.400 --> 00:28:43.000
Roughly speaking, they have clumsy and skillful information influence. We may not realize skillful influencing as influencing at all.

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:46.080
With clumsy influencing the goal is to draw our attention away. 

00:28:46.080 --> 00:28:50.320
Johan Bäckman (an activist working for the Russian government), for example, is involved in clumsy information influencing.

00:28:50.320 --> 00:28:54.720
When Johan Bäckman speaks for Russia we notice "Hey, he's speaking for Russia" 

00:28:54.720 --> 00:28:57.720
And we're pleased with ourselves for seeing this influence on information

00:28:57.720 --> 00:29:01.120
When, in fact, Bäckman's job (and that of people like him for Russia) is to draw our attention away as a diversion

00:29:01.120 --> 00:29:04.120
in order for the skillful information to take place somewhere else more effectively.

00:29:04.120 --> 00:29:07.080
We have former prime ministers on the boards of Russian banks.

00:29:07.080 --> 00:29:11.360
We have former prime ministers in charge of gas pipelines.

00:29:11.360 --> 00:29:15.800
We have a hockey team that plays in the KHL and so on.

00:29:15.800 --> 00:29:18.520
Maybe the real information influence of Russia is happening somewhere out there

00:29:18.520 --> 00:29:20.920
While we watch Johan Bäckman, thinking, "hey we notice this". 

00:29:20.920 --> 00:29:26.320
The Russians are good at this. As early as the 1920s, they founded the predecessor of the KGB,

00:29:26.320 --> 00:29:33.520
an information office whose mission was to influence the mind and politics of the press specifically through influential agents.

00:29:33.520 --> 00:29:39.800
It was the same in KGB, Putin has attended KGB school. This information influence is likely to continue by Russia.

00:29:39.800 --> 00:29:48.000
Lenin talked about useful idiots who may not realize they are serving the interests of Russia or the Soviet Union at any time. 

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:51.520
They think they're doing something good, peace movements for example. 

00:29:52.320 --> 00:29:54.760
They did not realize how they were actually used.

00:29:54.760 --> 00:30:00.480
They thought they were doing something good but ended up being largely part of Russia’s information geopolitics.

00:30:01.760 --> 00:30:06.240
The Russians have a wonderful belief in how they have to save Europe.

00:30:07.360 --> 00:30:10.560
In some sense, they are right, they have.

00:30:10.560 --> 00:30:15.440
They think that they must save Europe and unite the Slavic peoples.

00:30:16.600 --> 00:30:21.480
In history, they have saved Europe from Napoleon. Really, they beat Napoleon.

00:30:21.480 --> 00:30:26.160
They saved Europe from Hitler, fascism.

00:30:26.160 --> 00:30:31.960
Right now, I remember when I was on a business trip to Russia in the 1990s.

00:30:31.960 --> 00:30:36.520
I asked the Russian officers, "What are you doing there in Chechnya and why are you fighting there?"

00:30:36.520 --> 00:30:40.840
According to them, the Russians were there to defend Europe

00:30:40.840 --> 00:30:48.360
Against Islam, when Europeans themselves do not realize how great a threat Islam is and how much Russia is doing for Europe to prevent its spread.

00:30:48.360 --> 00:30:53.960
Really they believe in how their mission is to defend, protect and save Europe.

00:30:53.960 --> 00:30:58.720
They may not know against what, but in any case, they will always save us.

00:30:58.720 --> 00:31:00.160
Even if we don’t want to.

00:31:00.160 --> 00:31:10.080
Tolstoy supported that doctrine, as did Dugin, who is considered the geopolitical brain in the Kremlin.

00:31:10.080 --> 00:31:17.080
He pushed and is pushing hard for the view that Russia would save everyone, even if not asked.

00:31:18.320 --> 00:31:21.480
Russians see the world through history.

00:31:21.480 --> 00:31:26.800
I was talking about the conquest of the Poles and the time of the turmoil.

00:31:26.800 --> 00:31:30.720
Here in the bottom left is a merchant Kuzma Minin and Prince Dmitry.

00:31:30.720 --> 00:31:47.160
They reunited. Once again, the story features the people, and a prince who joined forces and defeated the Poles in Moscow before the end of the turmoil.

00:31:47.160 --> 00:31:54.920
Minin and Dmitri are immortalized in statues on the red square near the church in Moscow.

00:31:54.920 --> 00:32:06.400
In order for the Russians to not forget that the people and the prince reunited and joined forces, resulting in Russia being unbeatable.

00:32:06.400 --> 00:32:12.480
This is remembered in military parades annually, troops march past these statues.

00:32:12.480 --> 00:32:17.800
Remember, well, that's how it happened. When we joined forces the Poles lost.

00:32:17.800 --> 00:32:25.560
In Russia, the beginning of November is Unity Day (4th of Nov). It's the day when Minin and Dmitry beat the Poles.

00:32:25.560 --> 00:32:30.840
Near the former anniversary of the October Revolution, 7th of October.

00:32:30.840 --> 00:32:35.760
Next to it, the Unity Day was formed.

00:32:35.760 --> 00:32:40.560
Unity Day reminds us that when the people and the prince united, no one could do anything to beat the Russians.

00:32:40.560 --> 00:32:45.320
This is a reminder of how Russians think of everything through history and power.

00:32:45.320 --> 00:32:53.680
When Molotov told Stalin that the Russians should establish relations with the Vatican during World War II

00:32:53.680 --> 00:32:57.360
Stalin asked: "How many divisions does the pope have?"

00:32:57.360 --> 00:33:00.200
Molotov said: "Well, none at all," to which Stalin replied "Forget it."

00:33:00.200 --> 00:33:07.760
The Russians did not realize how one Polish Pope behind the Iron Curtain would be able to break the whole system.

00:33:07.760 --> 00:33:13.320
When there was a Polish Pope, if it was a CIA operation, it was an extremely well-planned operation. 

00:33:13.320 --> 00:33:17.120
If it was just a coincidence, it was a pretty good coincidence, at least in my opinion.

00:33:18.760 --> 00:33:24.840
Here's how Russians see us Finns. Pushkin is a national poet in Russia. 

00:33:24.840 --> 00:33:32.440
The Bronze Horseman is the first poem that the little girls with braids and the little boys memorize at school in Russia.

00:33:32.440 --> 00:33:37.960
This is the first poem they memorize in school. The Bronze Horseman by Pushkin.

00:33:37.960 --> 00:33:41.800
The poem tells the story of the founding of the city of St. Petersburg in the early 18th century.

00:33:41.800 --> 00:33:49.680
Read this and see what image these little girls and boys get of Finns or Chukhna.

00:33:49.680 --> 00:33:54.640
Very rarely is the word Chukhna actually written anywhere, but here it can be found in Pushkin.

00:33:54.640 --> 00:33:57.880
And what kind of people are Swedes? (according to the poem)

00:33:57.880 --> 00:34:11.200
(15 second pause)

00:34:11.200 --> 00:34:17.160
In other words, the city is founded to be a nuisance for the haughty, the Swedes.

00:34:18.320 --> 00:34:25.360
Before the city was established the area was mostly a swamp with a couple of cottages.

00:34:25.360 --> 00:34:28.400
“Where wretched Chukhna for shelter crowded”

00:34:28.400 --> 00:34:32.000
Chukhna, that is, us Finns.

00:34:32.000 --> 00:34:38.320
"The Finn, a miserable stepchild of nature", and it is actually put much sharper in the original version.

00:34:38.320 --> 00:34:44.920
I mean this poem has been translated positively for us Finns.

00:34:44.920 --> 00:34:50.400
(According to the poem) Finnish waves can bang their heads on the walls of St. Petersburg.

00:34:50.400 --> 00:35:03.040
In other words, this is the image that the children get of Finland and Sweden from an early age. This is where the thing starts.

00:35:03.040 --> 00:35:10.720
In Finland if someone were to teach similar things about Russians the teacher would probably get fired right away.

00:35:12.040 --> 00:35:16.560
Russia is technologically backward and has always been.

00:35:16.560 --> 00:35:22.120
Someone said that the Russian has invented nothing but a samovar and even there the faucet was stolen from the Germans.

00:35:22.120 --> 00:35:25.360
I don’t know if the story is true but that’s the saying.

00:35:25.360 --> 00:35:33.040
This is an interesting painting. Ilja Repin's painting Barge Haulers on the Volga.

00:35:33.040 --> 00:35:40.600
This is an interesting painting in the sense that Russia's backwardness is seen here.

00:35:40.600 --> 00:35:46.480
Not in these ferries but over there, in the right hand corner at the back. 

00:35:46.480 --> 00:35:51.200
There you can see a steamship from Germany.

00:35:51.200 --> 00:35:57.400
In other words, German ships began to operate on the Volga, not Russian ships.

00:35:57.400 --> 00:36:07.720
When these people pulled the ferry upstream, there was already new hope in the background, but it wasn't Russian hope, it was German imported goods.

00:36:07.720 --> 00:36:14.240
If you think about it, Peter the Great learned to build ships in Holland.

00:36:16.400 --> 00:36:20.800
The Russians themselves tried to build computers in the late 1970s they made a decision.

00:36:20.800 --> 00:36:27.640
"No, we don't have the capacity to do that, we have to copy IBM." The IBM 360 was the system that the Russians started to copy.

00:36:27.640 --> 00:36:34.640
The war in Afghanistan made procurement a little more difficult, but they still got IBM equipment through cover companies, including Japan.

00:36:34.640 --> 00:36:40.080
The equipment they dismantled upon receiving them, made similar parts, copied them and then assembled again.

00:36:40.080 --> 00:36:43.840
In the upper right hand corner is a Russian microchip that is a copy.

00:36:43.840 --> 00:36:49.440
About nuclear weapons. When Stalin realized the United States was developing nuclear weapons

00:36:49.440 --> 00:36:56.280
the Soviet intelligence service's most over-the-top intelligence priority was everything related to nuclear weapons. "Get it here."

00:36:56.280 --> 00:36:59.120
The Russians got the atom bomb a few years later.

00:36:59.120 --> 00:37:03.400
Pictured bottom left are individuals acquiring them (from the United States.)

00:37:03.400 --> 00:37:05.920
A few got put into an electric chair.

00:37:05.920 --> 00:37:10.960
In any case, the Soviet Union had stolen nuclear weapons data from the United States.

00:37:10.960 --> 00:37:19.560
Now what happens today. Russia does not have the capacity to develop artificial intelligence itself. The Chinese have it, the Russians do not.

00:37:20.720 --> 00:37:27.440
Putin has said: "Whoever masters artificial intelligence, he will become the ruler of the whole world.”

00:37:27.440 --> 00:37:34.560
It is certain that right now one of the most important tasks of intelligence services is to acquire everything related to artificial intelligence.

00:37:37.520 --> 00:37:42.080
Russian truth. This is interesting.

00:37:42.080 --> 00:37:47.800
After all, language tells how people think, how they perceive the world and how society thinks.

00:37:47.800 --> 00:37:53.240
The United States has two words for positive rights: "liberty" and "freedom" and so on.

00:37:53.240 --> 00:37:56.280
Russia has two words for the truth and three words for the lie. 

00:37:56.280 --> 00:37:58.760
It is certainly not a coincidence.

00:37:58.760 --> 00:38:04.800
There’s the word “pravda”, which is truth but not absolute truth.

00:38:04.800 --> 00:38:08.720
Rather the kind of truth that gets rid of awkward, wicked situations.

00:38:09.400 --> 00:38:17.920
It's like tactical truth. “Istina” is the opposite of a lie. 
Istina is true, as true as can be.

00:38:17.920 --> 00:38:24.400
But pravda is rather… sometimes it can be true, at other times not so true.

00:38:24.400 --> 00:38:32.800
Three words for lie: “Vranyo” is a white lie, but of the strategic level.

00:38:32.800 --> 00:38:37.280
It is also kind of a way to get rid of nasty situations.

00:38:37.280 --> 00:38:43.360
The Russians know it, we don't know it. We think that there is only truth and lie in the world

00:38:43.360 --> 00:38:48.360
It's just black and white, or plus and minus. We think so because we usually have it that way.

00:38:48.360 --> 00:38:53.320
The lie in Russia was born under Mongol rule

00:38:53.320 --> 00:39:01.200
During Mongol rule: Violence and lying were the way to survive. This tradition has been in their system ever since.

00:39:01.200 --> 00:39:06.200
Russia has the word “krugovaya poruka” (круговая порука), or gang guarantee.

00:39:06.200 --> 00:39:08.760
By the way, the Finnish word "porukka" (gang) comes from here.

00:39:08.760 --> 00:39:13.160
It means that when we have some set of people with a common goal.

00:39:13.160 --> 00:39:17.400
Be it the Kremlin leadership or the Russian armed forces or whatever.

00:39:17.400 --> 00:39:22.960
We have a common goal and I step out of the circle and lie to an outsider.

00:39:22.960 --> 00:39:31.880
My gang hears that I lie but they don't judge me as a liar

00:39:31.880 --> 00:39:41.040
Because they understand that I am using tactical truth (vranjo) to achieve the greater goals of our gang.

00:39:41.040 --> 00:39:48.960
The use of tactical truth, or a lie, is accepted if it is done for the benefit of the in-group. 

00:39:48.960 --> 00:39:52.120
Just like you can steal when you don’t steal too much or from the wrong guy.

00:39:52.120 --> 00:39:55.240
You also get to lie if you lie for the sake of the gang.

00:39:55.240 --> 00:40:00.320
For us in the West, the truth is black and white.

00:40:00.320 --> 00:40:05.520
There’s a good book from Masha Gessen that I have with me here.

00:40:05.520 --> 00:40:10.280
"The Future is History" Worth reading to anyone interested in this theme.

00:40:10.280 --> 00:40:14.240
Masha Gessen speaks of doublethink (as did Orwell in 1984).

00:40:14.240 --> 00:40:21.080
That is, at the kitchen table, different things are said than outside the home. This is similar.

00:40:21.080 --> 00:40:28.560
Everyone understands that Bob speaks very differently around the kitchen table than he does in public. Everyone understands why he does so.

00:40:28.560 --> 00:40:35.680
This is based on the in-group launching their own story.

00:40:35.680 --> 00:40:39.040
For example "We had nothing to do with the poisoning of Skripal."

00:40:39.040 --> 00:40:42.320
Or that "We have nothing to do with the shooting down of the Malaysian plane".

00:40:42.320 --> 00:40:45.800
This is based on the fact that we in the West, under the rule of law

00:40:45.800 --> 00:40:52.680
when we make an argument we need to be able to 100%, unequivocally prove the claim to be true.

00:40:53.720 --> 00:41:02.040
But when Russia makes an argument, there are always small gaps left here and there that we (westerners) start to think about, "Is that really so?"

00:41:02.040 --> 00:41:06.520
The notion of lie and truth works differently in Russia. 

00:41:06.520 --> 00:41:10.440
Examples: The Terijoki government (Russian attempt to make a puppet government for Finland in 1939) pushed the narrative

00:41:10.440 --> 00:41:12.880
that the working population of Finland supposedly was

00:41:12.880 --> 00:41:17.920
tired of the Mannerheim-Tanner (Marshal of the Finnish Defence Forces in 1939) fascist junta and formed a government to liberate the Finnish people.

00:41:17.920 --> 00:41:21.480
When the Russians came over they noticed it wasn’t quite so.

00:41:23.520 --> 00:41:25.960
Or this one.

00:41:25.960 --> 00:41:31.640
The president said "We have nothing to do with interfering in the 2016 U.S. presidential election".

00:41:31.640 --> 00:41:36.920
He says just like that. The Russians who see and hear this know that "We were there, but we didn't get caught." 

00:41:36.920 --> 00:41:40.800
Then the West thinks, "Well, who could it be, if it wasn’t the Russians?"

00:41:40.800 --> 00:41:45.720
Because we don't realize the use of Russian tactical truth.

00:41:47.720 --> 00:41:52.640
When they went to Crimea, Putin said, "They are not Russian forces."

00:41:52.640 --> 00:41:59.560
If our commander-in-chief of the Finnish Defence Forces were to deny that a Finnish soldier was a Finnish soldier, that would lead to unfortunate situations.

00:41:59.560 --> 00:42:07.120
The soldier would go on a strike or get depressed or something. But the Russians were proud that the president was able to use tactical truth.

00:42:07.120 --> 00:42:12.600
Putin said "They are not Russian forces." We started thinking here in the west, "Well, who are they then? Where did they come from?"

00:42:12.600 --> 00:42:19.240
They had two or three days to take over Crimea completely.

00:42:19.240 --> 00:42:22.360
Then Putin remembered, "Oh, they were Russian troops after all".

00:42:23.480 --> 00:42:28.720
Or this shooting down of a Malaysian plane.

00:42:30.000 --> 00:42:38.920
It has been proven unequivocally that the missile that shot that plane down was from the Russian 53rd Air Defense Brigade.

00:42:38.920 --> 00:42:44.360
The wildest stories that were moving in Russia were that, when the situation was at its hottest

00:42:44.360 --> 00:42:49.520
that these people were already dead there on the plane. This story was spread.

00:42:49.520 --> 00:42:53.800
Those people who died in the accident did not die in the attack but they were already dead (before the missile struck the plane.)

00:42:53.800 --> 00:42:57.720
But no one questioned it because the Russians knew it was a tactical truth.

00:42:57.720 --> 00:43:03.680
They did not question how the captain agreed to fly a plane full of dead people, about to be shot down.

00:43:03.680 --> 00:43:06.320
No one questioned it because they knew it was a tactical truth.

00:43:06.320 --> 00:43:15.560
Or, another story, in the Donbass region brave miners fight the fascist junta in Kiev.

00:43:15.560 --> 00:43:22.600
However, some so-called civilian protesters had apparently forgotten to remove their Russian Armed Forces tags. 

00:43:22.600 --> 00:43:29.720
Or "We have nothing to do with the hacking of the DNC, the US Democratic Party."

00:43:29.720 --> 00:43:33.680
In fact, they got caught, both the GRU, the Russian military intelligence service

00:43:33.680 --> 00:43:39.440
and the FSB, the civilian intelligence, both caught on servers.

00:43:39.440 --> 00:43:43.880
Or that “We don’t have anything to do with the poisoning of Skripal.”

00:43:43.880 --> 00:43:48.120
Except that there was a Russian intelligence colonel

00:43:48.120 --> 00:43:53.400
who had received the Hero of the Russian Federation honorary medal from Putin.

00:43:53.400 --> 00:43:59.200
There was also a doctor present who was tasked with making sure Chepiga, who was performing the poisoning operation on Skripal

00:43:59.200 --> 00:44:01.760
would not be exposed to the poison himself.

00:44:01.760 --> 00:44:09.840
The funniest thing here is that Chepiga's grandmother, who lives near Arkhangelsk, in her foolishness had published a picture

00:44:09.840 --> 00:44:14.720
of Chepiga receiving the medal from Putin himself.

00:44:14.720 --> 00:44:18.760
You never guess what happened to the Grandma after that? Grandma disappeared.

00:44:20.520 --> 00:44:24.240
Or that “we’re not involved in Eastern Ukraine".

00:44:24.240 --> 00:44:29.120
Here is the tomb of a 21-year-old paratrooper. In Pskov. Fallen in the Donbass.

00:44:29.120 --> 00:44:42.600
We need to understand that the use of Russian truth and falsehood is completely different from our thinking.

00:44:42.600 --> 00:44:46.200
If they say something, they won’t necessarily mean it

00:44:46.200 --> 00:44:53.760
but the tactical truth is meant as an instrument to slip through a slightly open doorway to get out of a nasty situation.

00:44:53.760 --> 00:44:57.000
So what could destabilize Russia?

00:44:57.000 --> 00:45:01.800
Middle class? Internal conflict in the system? Activation of the opposition?

00:45:01.800 --> 00:45:05.040
Some threats have been eliminated already.

00:45:05.040 --> 00:45:11.120
Change in the energy sector? Whatever would happen to Russia, they have such good reserves that they don’t bump

00:45:11.120 --> 00:45:14.520
Even if the price of oil drops to $40 a barrel.

00:45:14.520 --> 00:45:17.960
Nationalism is not a problem when it is channeled.

00:45:17.960 --> 00:45:22.080
Chechnya has been treated, there Kadyrov pulls the strings at the moment. 

00:45:22.080 --> 00:45:26.160
The global recession is not really a problem to Russia since they are in a recession all the time anyway.

00:45:26.160 --> 00:45:30.080
But these are the ones that could make a difference.

00:45:30.080 --> 00:45:33.200
This is what the Russians fear: a time of turmoil.

00:45:33.200 --> 00:45:39.080
A time of turmoil as the time before Romanov was elected leader.

00:45:39.080 --> 00:45:47.600
This is their horror, a time of turmoil. The Russians also use the 1990s as a time of turmoil.

00:45:47.600 --> 00:45:54.120
When there's a weak leader, the country is in turmoil. 

00:45:54.120 --> 00:45:58.680
That is, even if it hurts a little, they prefer a strong leader, because under a strong leader chaos is absent.

00:45:58.680 --> 00:46:05.520
This right hand image in the top corner is interesting. The picture is from Leningrad. Sobtshakin, mayor.

00:46:05.520 --> 00:46:10.400
Behind him is a gray official named Vladimir Putin.

00:46:10.400 --> 00:46:18.000
He’s not really the protagonist of this image yet but the next person who appears in the image is the protagonist of the image. Viktor Zolotov.

00:46:18.800 --> 00:46:25.960
He is a lathe operator by profession. Putin's judo friends. Let's get back to Zolotov later, but remember the name, Zolotov.

00:46:25.960 --> 00:46:33.280
Putin's judo friends. Lathe operator by profession, by education and by sophistication.

00:46:36.160 --> 00:46:39.920
The Russians have a fear of internal unrest.

00:46:39.920 --> 00:46:47.200
Putin, who fears internal unrest, has elevated this Viktor Zolotov as a boyar

00:46:47.200 --> 00:46:54.800
This guy, a lathe operator by education, first followed Yeltsin to Moscow

00:46:54.800 --> 00:47:00.720
After which he was made 1.5 years ago (2017) the Commander of the National Guard, three-star general.

00:47:02.160 --> 00:47:06.440
I have been in military school for six years and I retired at the rank of Colonel.

00:47:06.440 --> 00:47:12.640
He has studied to be a turner and he is a three-star general because he belongs to the boyar.

00:47:12.640 --> 00:47:16.680
He is trustworthy because he has been Putin’s judo buddy since the 1970s

00:47:16.680 --> 00:47:24.240
Look at that look, he would even set his hand on fire because of Putin.

00:47:24.240 --> 00:47:30.000
In the background of this image is a picture from an act that came into power a few years ago, a law that empowers the National Guard.

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:36.400
Putin cannot rely entirely on the armed forces. The National Guard was established around Putin to protect him.

00:47:36.400 --> 00:47:41.120
Among other things, the National Guard was tasked with quelling internal unrest.

00:47:41.120 --> 00:47:43.360
They are allowed to use violence

00:47:43.360 --> 00:47:51.240
But because the law is humane, they are allowed to fire at protesters, but they are not allowed to fire at such protesters who are women and pregnant.

00:47:51.240 --> 00:47:58.960
That is, the National Guard must look among the protesters not to shoot pregnant women because the law is humane.

00:47:58.960 --> 00:48:01.920
Zolotov is a tough guy.

00:48:01.920 --> 00:48:12.480
Navalnyj challenged Zolotov. Of course, since Zolotov is high on the scale of the boyars, he is entitled to high levels of corruption.

00:48:12.480 --> 00:48:20.160
He has a pretty large amount of assets. Navalnyj, who hates this corruption, found Zolotov's property

00:48:20.160 --> 00:48:24.120
And challenged Zolotov to a conversation on television.

00:48:24.120 --> 00:48:26.960
Navalnyj said: "I'm challenging you to a conversation in a television about this corruption."

00:48:26.960 --> 00:48:33.080
Zolotov, who is an old judoka, replied, "I'll challenge you to a duel, in a ring or on a judo mat, I'll make you minced meat."

00:48:33.080 --> 00:48:39.240
In a western world would a high-ranking police commander say to make minced meat out of someone, how long would he stay in office?

00:48:39.240 --> 00:48:41.600
But this kind of discourse is business as usual in Russia.

00:48:44.280 --> 00:48:47.920
This is what they are afraid of: Repetition of the Maidan.

00:48:47.920 --> 00:48:52.640
This is where Putin took a little back when they started raising the retirement age,

00:48:52.640 --> 00:49:00.360
so a little was taken back because it was seen that people simply did not like this increase in retirement age.

00:49:01.360 --> 00:49:09.440
Russia's change. If we look at how Russia has developed. Tsarist Russia had an authoritarian system of leadership.

00:49:09.440 --> 00:49:15.000
The Tsar had received his power from god and was infallible.

00:49:15.000 --> 00:49:20.920
Corruption was intense, opposition was persecuted, Westerners were portrayed as a threat

00:49:20.920 --> 00:49:27.040
Autocracy, Russia had a messianic mission, they sought regional expansion and believed in Russianness.

00:49:27.040 --> 00:49:31.240
Then the power of the Tsars collapsed and the Soviet Union was established.

00:49:31.240 --> 00:49:38.160
There was an authoritarian system of leadership, there was corruption, there was opposition persecution

00:49:38.160 --> 00:49:41.440
the West was described as a threat, there was a sham democracy

00:49:41.440 --> 00:49:46.840
they had a messianic mission, their mission was to spread communism to Cuba, Angola and so on in exactly the same way.

00:49:46.840 --> 00:49:53.120
The messianic mission of spreading communism.

00:49:53.120 --> 00:49:57.400
Regional enlargement efforts and they believed in Russianness. 

00:49:57.400 --> 00:49:59.360
That is, although the Soviet Union was the home of the peoples

00:49:59.360 --> 00:50:06.640
The Russian part was still the leading class, although it was not highlighted

00:50:06.640 --> 00:50:09.960
Then came the time of turmoil. Everything went a little bad.

00:50:09.960 --> 00:50:15.720
Power was decentralized, the regions gained a lot of power. Corruption did not disappear.

00:50:15.720 --> 00:50:21.800
Russia had freedom of speech in the 1990s. They even thought about NATO membership. The West was no longer a threat.

00:50:21.800 --> 00:50:33.000
There was an era of democracy that turned it into a curse word and an ugly word in the minds of the Russian people because they were financially on their knees.

00:50:33.000 --> 00:50:39.160
Identity was lost. They were trying to save the remnants of their empire through wars in the 1990s

00:50:39.160 --> 00:50:44.040
Chechnya's first war and so on. Western culture began to push itself into Russia.

00:50:44.040 --> 00:50:48.680
But then, thankfully in the Russian mind, along came a strong leader who saved everything.

00:50:48.680 --> 00:50:51.440
Let's go to Russia in 2000. Putin's Russia.

00:50:51.440 --> 00:50:57.960
There is an authoritarian system of leadership, corruption, persecution of the opposition, the West is described as a threat

00:50:57.960 --> 00:51:04.320
a guided democracy, Russia has a messianic mission, regional enlargement efforts, and a belief in Russianness.

00:51:04.320 --> 00:51:13.200
If we look at when Russia was liberated from the Mongols in the 15th century to the present day

00:51:13.200 --> 00:51:19.320
This bottom red line is an authoritarian system of leadership, the west is the enemy and so on.

00:51:19.320 --> 00:51:32.680
And that small yellow dot is a time when there was freedom of speech, democracy and the West was not seen as a threat.

00:51:33.720 --> 00:51:41.200
In other words, the one who thinks Russia would change, you can think so, but I don't agree.

00:51:41.200 --> 00:51:46.440
This anomaly of the 1990s was a coincidence. This will continue as long as it continues.

00:51:46.440 --> 00:51:52.800
Let's see how it goes. Homo re-sovieticus is born.

00:51:52.800 --> 00:51:59.800
In 2017, Levada conducted a survey for Russians. 10 most significant people in world history (according to Russians.)

00:51:59.800 --> 00:52:03.240
Stalin 38 %.

00:52:03.240 --> 00:52:16.240
Quite a hard figure when, according to some sources, 20-25 million people were executed or died in camps by Stalin.

00:52:16.240 --> 00:52:19.360
34% said Putin is the toughest man in world history.

00:52:21.040 --> 00:52:27.280
Half of Russians in 2012 considered the purges by Stalin a political crime, in 2017 only 39% did.

00:52:28.160 --> 00:52:30.840
An increasing number of Russians know nothing of the purges.

00:52:30.840 --> 00:52:37.280
This Masha Gessen, whose book I showed, is talking about suicidal terrorism in Russia.

00:52:37.280 --> 00:52:44.480
If you think of Nazi Germany’s phenomena of Nazis killing Jews, they were different gangs, and so on.

00:52:44.480 --> 00:52:47.600
But in Russia people killed each other.

00:52:47.600 --> 00:52:57.720
families and clans were mixed up so that there were victims and executions in every family and house

00:52:57.720 --> 00:53:03.920
This matter was not settled in Russia, as it was in Germany.

00:53:03.920 --> 00:53:09.000
People are told: "The Nazis were evil and the Jews were victims and this can not happen again."

00:53:09.000 --> 00:53:14.040
There has never been such dealing with the subject in Russia because they were so messed up.

00:53:14.040 --> 00:53:16.480
There was a shooter and a victim from the same nuclear family.

00:53:16.480 --> 00:53:17.920
There was a shooter and a victim from the same extended family.

00:53:17.920 --> 00:53:22.480
It never got there to a situation where it would be dealt with what really went through and what really happened.

00:53:22.480 --> 00:53:26.920
That's why they still consider Stalin a tough guy, and that’s pretty worrying.

00:53:26.920 --> 00:53:31.640
Worship of the past. They want to go back to that kind of imaginary past

00:53:31.640 --> 00:53:37.800
There was no such thing as the imaginary past they want to go back to but they think there was.

00:53:37.800 --> 00:53:41.840
Stalin’s glorification, longing back for the Tsarist Empire and so on.

00:53:41.840 --> 00:53:45.680
Then there is the desire to correct the historical injustices experienced by Russia.

00:53:45.680 --> 00:53:51.560
Let's face it. All nations have experienced injustices. We Finns lost Karelia. But we won't shout for it anymore. We were beaten and so be it.

00:53:51.560 --> 00:53:57.600
But the Russians are digging for the injustices they have been wronged for and seeking redress for any reason.

00:53:57.600 --> 00:54:02.480
Currently in the Crimea. Crimea was given to Ukraine in 1954.

00:54:02.480 --> 00:54:06.840
The Russians took it back because it was just a correction of a historical injustice and so on.

00:54:06.840 --> 00:54:12.360
They have a longing for a Soviet Union that never existed in reality.

00:54:12.360 --> 00:54:22.000
Here is a Russian pensioner, a civil servant, a teacher, a student and a schoolboy. The picture has their ages and years of birth.

00:54:23.080 --> 00:54:34.680
Gessen is talking of such an imaginary past, which is in fact a romanticized, glorified Soviet era, which it was not.

00:54:34.680 --> 00:54:39.280
The more the time goes on, the finer the times become in people’s minds and heads.

00:54:39.280 --> 00:54:42.240
Then there is this democracy, which is a time of turmoil.

00:54:43.120 --> 00:54:46.600
Then Gessen uses the term "a future that does not exist".

00:54:46.600 --> 00:54:49.680
Here’s in what era people of different ages today in Russia lived.

00:54:49.680 --> 00:54:58.560
When we expand it to a wider timeline, we can make a conclusion about what the schoolboy or student is thinking.

00:54:58.560 --> 00:55:02.480
He has actually lived under Putin's rule all his life.

00:55:02.480 --> 00:55:07.000
He has heard all his life on television that "the west threatens us"

00:55:07.000 --> 00:55:09.920
"We are a besieged fort and we are at war" and so on.

00:55:11.120 --> 00:55:12.920
This is very challenging.

00:55:12.920 --> 00:55:15.440
What can happen in Russia?

00:55:15.440 --> 00:55:20.400
The period of stagnation will continue until Putin leaves.

00:55:21.880 --> 00:55:25.760
Or there will be a harsher period, Stalin's time part two. Another purge.

00:55:25.760 --> 00:55:29.920
Development stops and repression begins, the Iron Curtain.

00:55:29.920 --> 00:55:35.960
Or the whole system will collapse as it did in February 1917.

00:55:36.920 --> 00:55:41.160
Or Russia democratizes, which I personally don’t believe.

00:55:41.160 --> 00:55:49.560
Or it polarizes with westernizers and slavophiles, the west and the east will begin to struggle with each other again.

00:55:51.120 --> 00:56:05.800
I talked earlier about princes. There are two princes here today. We have a good tsar who is infallible and he will retire in 2024, probably.

00:56:05.800 --> 00:56:12.640
A new tsar will be elected to replace him. Here are two potential candidates.

00:56:12.640 --> 00:56:22.640
The prince must be a tough guy. He needs to be able to guarantee a peaceful rest of the life for the retiring tsar.

00:56:22.640 --> 00:56:30.040
Just as Putin guaranteed Yeltsin's life so that Yeltsin lived in peace from all legal action until he died.

00:56:30.040 --> 00:56:36.720
In exactly the same way, Putin is now looking for such a prince. Medvedev is too soft. He can't do it. 

00:56:36.720 --> 00:56:39.960
Here are two candidates. This is Djumin.

00:56:39.960 --> 00:56:47.520
The Russian princely story requires that the prince is a hero. Before he becomes the infallible tsar he must be the hero.

00:56:47.520 --> 00:56:56.120
He is somehow heroic. Djumin is heroic, he has been awarded the title of Russian hero.

00:56:56.120 --> 00:57:04.840
He rescued Yanukovych in February 2014 from the clutches of fascists in Kiev.

00:57:04.840 --> 00:57:12.600
That is, he led the Yanukovych rescue operation from there when, according to the story, the fascists came to power in Kiev.

00:57:12.600 --> 00:57:19.200
He earned the title of Russian hero. He was a major general and Deputy Minister of Defence.

00:57:19.200 --> 00:57:27.600
He has then been recovered in that Tula area. He has earned the hero's cloak, he is safe in Tula.

00:57:27.600 --> 00:57:34.640
He has been castled. Russian chess gamers like to castle. Djumin has been castled there to the Tula area to wait

00:57:34.640 --> 00:57:43.240
It is close to Moscow. In an area where nothing should go wrong, i.e. the hero will no longer do anything wrong before 2024.

00:57:43.240 --> 00:57:48.320
And he waits there, learning administration in a good Tula district.

00:57:48.320 --> 00:57:52.360
This second candidate, Zinitsev, is currently Minister of Emergency Situations.

00:57:52.360 --> 00:57:58.400
The Minister of Emergency Situations is always the one who saves the Russians whether it is a flood or whatever.

00:57:58.400 --> 00:58:03.080
That is, he will also receive the title of Russian hero.

00:58:03.080 --> 00:58:06.760
He will save the Russians at some point before 2024.

00:58:06.760 --> 00:58:11.320
He has a pretty hard track record when we look at where he has worked in the past.

00:58:11.320 --> 00:58:16.360
KGB, FSB, FSO, a man of the system. He has been very close to Putin. 

00:58:16.360 --> 00:58:18.920
These two candidates look similar to each other, funnily enough.

00:58:18.920 --> 00:58:24.920
The only difference is that Djumin plays as a goalkeeper for the hockey team in Putin.

00:58:24.920 --> 00:58:29.560
Djumin is a good goalkeeper except when Putin shoots then that’s when it usually goes all the way to the goal.

00:58:29.560 --> 00:58:35.000
He also knows this boyar game quite well.

00:58:35.000 --> 00:58:43.080
Here it was. Let's go back. Sociological research. Putin's support is beginning to decline. (Fall 2018)

00:58:43.080 --> 00:58:49.280
There is talk that Putin is responsible for the problems of Russia where the armed forces are not so important.

00:58:49.280 --> 00:58:55.400
More important is the well-being of the people. 20 million people live below the poverty line.

00:58:55.400 --> 00:59:02.520
22 % of the population can only buy essential food. Yes, little bubbles are bubbling under the surface.

00:59:04.640 --> 00:59:13.280
Here is a statement by protester (Olga Koltsova) in which she says “Either those in power are aware of the mood and are listening to the people or"

00:59:13.280 --> 00:59:18.800
"some kind of social explosions will rise up. When the lid of the boiler is closed very tightly, it will eventually fly into the air.”

00:59:18.800 --> 00:59:24.680
Just like in February 1917 and in the November Revolution.

00:59:24.680 --> 00:59:33.000
When the lid is too tight then something could happen. This is her view. This interview was conducted a week ago (November 2018).

00:59:33.000 --> 00:59:37.720
It is difficult to say where Russia is going and what is happening.

00:59:37.720 --> 00:59:46.480
This is the last picture. This is a demonstration from Moscow in September 2018.

00:59:46.480 --> 00:59:51.560
This may be the future of Russia.

00:59:51.560 --> 01:00:03.520
This person probably belongs to the group that gets their information from the internet, he does not belong to the 80% filtered television population.

01:00:03.520 --> 01:00:08.840
This may be the future in 10-15 years.

01:00:08.840 --> 01:00:19.080
Sometimes by 2030 something might happen if the lid does not bounce up before the next presidential election in 2024.

01:00:19.080 --> 01:00:21.480
Alright. I will end the presentation here.

